Q42_15_TEXT: "Signature" style alone does not determine artistic originality or authenticity. Contemporary art and theory already demonstrates that not only the image/object, but also the context of it's display and its mode of dissemination are integral parts of the works' ultimate meaning, reception, and "originality." (Warhol soup cans, Duchamp Urinal, Most all of Jeff Koons, and Richard Prince are artists who modify existing works through significant alterations of context, changing thier meaning, exhibition value, and use value)) That said, any applied art, such as that of a graphic designer, who is working in an applied marketplace (rather than a speculative/philosophical marketplace), should have monetary rights to their work. Particularly if it is being used in a similar marketplace as the "original." I'm not sure what the laws are about this but they do exist. There's an interesting case involving the Painter Luc Tuymans and the photojournalist whose image he swiped for a painting . .. .  In other words Stye alone is not the defining factor of art.

Q42_15_TEXT: I feel like this discussion is almost beside the point as of 2023, when it has already proven impossible to properly track attribution and redistribute compensation to any artist whose work was (probably illegally) scraped to feed the AI models used to make "derivatives" that often truly aren't (due to often-spurious or even impossible-to-prove correlations between individual artist styles, genre norms, and model outputs).  I love the idea of everybody making passive income for their contributions to the commons but as AI art becomes more popular it will just drive the price of art down generally, making a creative living even harder than it is...we're all getting automated out of jobs, not just the artists, and the real issue is how all of this just helps condense all economic value in the hands of sociopathic tech barons who refuse to acknowledge they owe anybody anything for their obscene wealth. We're all complicit in this BS, too.  And perfect systems that keep IP regulated in perpetuity mean the commons will eventually evaporate entirely and end up in the hands of like five people licensing our own lives back to us.
